{"cursor":"3091","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Wei Yuan' (, April 23, 1794âMarch 26, 1857), [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/638916/Wei-\nYuan EncyclopÃ¦dia Britannica] born 'Wei Yuanda' (é­è¿è¾¾), courtesy names\n'Moshen' (é»æ·±) and 'Hanshi' (æ±å£«), was a Chinese scholar from Shaoyang, Hunan. He\nmoved to Yangzhou in 1831, where he remained for the rest of his life. Wei\nobtained the provincial degree ([[juren]]) in the Imperial examinations and\nsubsequently worked in the secretariat of several prominent statesmen, such as\nLin Zexu. Wei was deeply concerned with the crisis facing China in the early\n19th century; while he remained loyal to the Qing Dynasty, he also sketched a\nnumber of proposals for the improvement of the administration of the empire.\n\nFrom an early age, Wei espoused the New Text school of Confucianism and became a\nvocal member of the statecraft school, which advocated practical learning in\nopposition to the allegedly barren evidentiary scholarship as represented by\nscholars like Dai Zhen. Among other things, Wei advocated sea transport of grain\nto the capital instead of using the Grand Canal and he also advocated a\nstrengthening of the Qing Empire's frontier defense. In order to alleviate the\ndemographic crisis in China proper, Wei also spoke in favor of large scale\nemigration of Han Chinese into Xinjiang.\n\nLater in his career he became increasingly concerned with the threat from the\nWestern powers and maritime defense. He wrote A Military History of the Qing\nDynasty (èæ­¦è¨, ShÃ¨ngwu Ji) and a narrative work on the Opium War (éåæ´èå¾æ«è¨,\nDaoguang Yangsou Zhengfu Ji). Today, he is mostly known for his 1844 work,\nIllustrated Treatise on the Maritime Kingdoms (æµ·ååå¿, Haiguo TuzhÃ¬), which\nconsists of Western material collected by Lin Zexu during and after the First\nOpium War.\n","linknr":136,"url":"Wei_Yuan","recorded":1375066239,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Wei_Y